VSMS König Albert ("His Majesty's Ship King Albert")[a] was the fourth vessel of the Kaiser\ufffdclass of battleships of the Imperial German Navy.
p2
aV[b] König Albert's keel was laid on 17 July 1910 at the Schichau-Werke dockyard in Danzig.
p3
aVShe was launched on 27 April 1912 and was commissioned into the fleet on 31 July 1913.
p4
aVThe ship was equipped with ten 30.5-centimeter (12.0\ufffdin) guns in five twin turrets, and had a top speed of 22.1 knots (40.9\ufffdkm/h; 25.4\ufffdmph).
p5
aVKönig Albert was assigned to the III Battle Squadron and later the IV Battle Squadron of the High Seas Fleet for the majority of her career, including World War I.
p6
aVAlong with her four sister ships, Kaiser, Friedrich der Grosse, Kaiserin, and Prinzregent Luitpold, König Albert participated in most of the major fleet operations of World War I, though she was in drydock for maintenance during the Battle of Jutland between 31 May and 1 June 1916.
p7
aVAs a result, she was the only battleship actively serving with the fleet that missed the largest naval battle of the war.
p8
aVThe ship was also involved in Operation Albion, an amphibious assault on the Russian-held islands in the Gulf of Riga, in late 1917.
p9
aVAfter Germany's defeat in the war and the signing of the Armistice in November 1918, König Albert and most of the capital ships of the High Seas Fleet were interned by the Royal Navy in Scapa Flow.
p10
aVThe ships were disarmed and reduced to skeleton crews while the Allied powers negotiated the final version of the Treaty of Versailles.
p11
aVOn 21 June 1919, days before the treaty was signed, the commander of the interned fleet, Rear Admiral Ludwig von Reuter, ordered the fleet to be scuttled to ensure that the British would not be able to seize the ships.
p12
aVKönig Albert was raised in July 1935 and subsequently broken up for scrap in 1936.
