VThe Madagascan sunset moth (Chrysiridia rhipheus) is a day-flying moth of the family Uraniidae.
p15
aVIt is considered one of the most impressive and appealing-looking lepidopterans.
p16
aVFamous worldwide, it is featured in most coffee table books on Lepidoptera and is much sought after by collectors.
p17
aVIt is very colourful, though the iridescent parts of the wings do not have pigment; rather the colours originate from optical interference.
p18
aVAdults have a wingspan of 7\u20139\ufffdcm (2.8\u20133.5\ufffdin).
p19
aVDru Drury, who described the moth in 1773, placed it in the genus Papilio, considering it a butterfly.
p20
aVJacob Hübner placed it in the moth genus Chrysiridia in 1823.
p21
aVLater redescriptions led to junior synonyms such as Chrysiridia madagascariensis (Lesson, 1831).
p22
aVAt first the moth was thought to be from China or Bengal, but was later found to be endemic to Madagascar.
p23
aVIt is found throughout the year in most parts of the island, with peak populations between March and August, and smallest numbers between October and December.
p24
aVFemales lay about 80 eggs under the leaves of Omphalea spp.
p25
aVThe caterpillars are whitish-yellow with black spots and red feet and are covered in club-ended black setae.
p26
aVSilk spun from the mouth helps the caterpillars hold onto smooth leaves and climb back to the plant when they fall.
p27
aVAfter completing four instars, the caterpillars spin an open network cocoon.
p28
aVThe pupal stage lasts from 17 to 23 days.
p29
aVChrysiridia rhipheus is the sole specialist herbivore of the four species of Omphalea in Madagascar.
p30
aVOmphalea is toxic: the toxins are sequestered by the feeding caterpillar and retained in the pupal and adult stages.
p31
aVThousands of these moths migrate between the eastern and western ranges of their host plants.
