VThe United States Bicentennial coinage was a set of circulating commemorative coins, consisting of a quarter, half dollar and dollar struck by the United States Mint in 1975 and 1976.
p34
aVRegardless of when struck, each coin bears the double date 1776\u20131976 on the normal obverses for the Washington quarter, Kennedy half dollar and Eisenhower dollar.
p35
aVNo coins dated 1975 of any of the three denominations were minted.
p36
aVGiven past abuses in the system, the Mint advocated against the issuance of commemorative coins starting in the 1950s.
p37
aVBeginning in 1971, members of Congress introduced bills to authorize coins to honor the United States Bicentennial, which would occur in 1976.
p38
aVThe Mint, through its director, Mary Brooks, initially opposed such proposals, but later supported them, and Congress passed legislation requiring the temporary redesign of the reverse of the quarter, half dollar and dollar.
p39
aVA nationwide competition resulted in designs of a Colonial drummer for the quarter, Independence Hall for the half dollar and the Liberty Bell superimposed against the moon for the dollar.
p40
aVAll three coins remain common today, due to the quantity struck.
p41
aVCirculation pieces were in copper nickel; Congress also mandated 45,000,000 part-silver pieces be struck for collectors.
p42
aVThe Mint sold over half of the part-silver coins before melting the remainder after withdrawing them from sale in 1986.
p43
aVDue to the large mintage, the pieces remain common today, and the quarter can still be found in circulation.
