VThe Battle of Towton was fought during the English Wars of the Roses on 29 March 1461, near the village of the same name in Yorkshire.
p60
aVIt was the "largest and bloodiest battle ever fought on English soil".
p61
aVAccording to chroniclers, more than 50,000\ufffdsoldiers from the Houses of York and Lancaster fought for hours amidst a snowstorm on that day, which was Palm Sunday.
p62
aVA newsletter circulated a week after the battle reported that 28,000 died on the battlefield.
p63
aVThe engagement brought about a monarchical change in England\u2014Edward IV displaced Henry VI as King of England, driving the head of the Lancastrians and his key supporters out of the country.
p64
aVContemporary accounts described Henry VI as peaceful and pious, not suited for the violent dynastic civil wars, such as the War of the Roses.
p65
aVHe suffered from periods of insanity while his inherent benevolence eventually required his wife, Margaret of Anjou, to assume control of his kingdom, which contributed to his own downfall.
p66
aVHis ineffectual rule had encouraged the nobles' schemes to establish control over him, and the situation deteriorated into a civil war between the supporters of his house and those of Richard Plantagenet, 3rd Duke of York.
p67
aVAfter the Yorkists captured Henry in 1460, the English parliament passed an Act of Accord to let York and his line succeed Henry as king.
p68
aVHenry's consort, Margaret of Anjou, refused to accept the dispossession of her son's right to the throne and, along with fellow Lancastrian malcontents, raised an army.
p69
aVRichard of York was killed at the Battle of Wakefield and his titles, including the claim to the throne, passed to his eldest son Edward.
p70
aVNobles, who were previously hesitant to support Richard's claim to the throne, regarded the Lancastrians to have reneged on the Act\u2014a legal agreement\u2014and Edward found enough backing to denounce Henry and declare himself king.
p71
aVThe Battle of Towton was to affirm the victor's right to rule over England through force of arms.
p72
aVOn reaching the battlefield, the Yorkists found themselves heavily outnumbered.
p73
aVPart of their force under John de Mowbray, 3rd Duke of Norfolk, had yet to arrive.
p74
aVThe Yorkist leader Lord Fauconberg turned the tables by ordering his archers to take advantage of the strong wind to outrange their enemies.
p75
aVThe one-sided missile exchange\u2014Lancastrian arrows fell short of the Yorkist ranks\u2014provoked the Lancastrians into abandoning their defensive positions.
p76
aVThe ensuing hand-to-hand combat lasted hours, exhausting the combatants.
p77
aVThe arrival of Norfolk's men reinvigorated the Yorkists and, encouraged by Edward, they routed their foes.
p78
aVMany Lancastrians were killed while fleeing; some trampled each other and others drowned in the rivers.
p79
aVSeveral who were taken as prisoners were executed.
p80
aVThe power of the House of Lancaster was severely reduced after this battle.
p81
aVHenry fled the country, and many of his most powerful followers were dead or in exile after the engagement, letting Edward rule England uninterrupted for nine\ufffdyears, before a brief restoration of Henry to the throne.
p82
aVLater generations remembered the battle as depicted in William Shakespeare's dramatic adaptation of Henry's life\u2014Henry VI, Part 3, Act\ufffd2, Scene\ufffd5.
p83
aVIn 1929, the Towton Cross was erected on the battlefield to commemorate the event.
p84
aVVarious archaeological remains and mass graves related to the battle were found in the area centuries after the engagement.
