VA Vindication of the Rights of Men, in a Letter to the Right Honourable Edmund Burke; Occasioned by His Reflections on the Revolution in France (1790) is a political pamphlet, written by the 18th-century British feminist Mary Wollstonecraft, which attacks aristocracy and advocates republicanism.
p87
aVWollstonecraft's was the first response in a pamphlet war sparked by the publication of Edmund Burke's Reflections on the Revolution in France (1790), a defence of constitutional monarchy, aristocracy, and the Church of England.
p88
aVWollstonecraft attacked not only hereditary privilege, but also the rhetoric that Burke used to defend it.
p89
aVMost of Burke's detractors deplored what they viewed as his theatrical pity for Marie Antoinette, but Wollstonecraft was unique in her love of Burke's gendered language.
p90
aVBy saying the sublime and the beautiful, terms first established by Burke himself in A Philosophical Enquiry into the Origin of Our Ideas of the Sublime and Beautiful (1756), she kept his rhetoric as well as his argument.
p91
aVIn her first unabashedly feminist critique, which Wollstonecraft scholar Claudia Johnson describes as unsurpassed in its argumentative force, Wollstonecraft indicts Burke's justification of an equal society founded on the passivity of women.
p92
aVIn her arguments for republican virtue, Wollstonecraft invokes an emerging middle-class ethos in opposition to what she views as the vice-ridden aristocratic code of manners.
p93
aVDriven by an Enlightenment belief in progress, she derides Burke for relying on tradition and custom.
p94
aVShe describes an idyllic country life in which each family has a farm sufficient for its needs.
p95
aVWollstonecraft contrasts her utopian picture of society, drawn with what she claims is genuine feeling, with Burke's false theatrical tableaux.
p96
aVThe Rights of Men was successful: it was reviewed by every major periodical of the day and the first edition sold out in three weeks.
p97
aVHowever, upon the publication of the second edition (the first to carry Wollstonecraft's name on the title page), the reviews began to evaluate the text not only as a political pamphlet but also as the work of a female writer.
p98
aVThey contrasted Wollstonecraft's "passion" with Burke's "reason" and spoke condescendingly of the text and its female author.
p99
aVThis analysis of the Rights of Men prevailed until the 1970s, when feminist scholars began to read Wollstonecraft's texts with more care and called attention to their intellectualism.
