VSirius is the brightest star in the night sky.
p132
aVWith a visual apparent magnitude of \u22121.46, it is almost twice as bright as Canopus, the next brightest star.
p133
aVThe name "Sirius" is derived from the Ancient Greek: \u03a3\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 Seirios ("glowing" or "scorcher").
p134
aVThe star has the Bayer designation Alpha Canis Majoris (\u03b1 CMa).
p135
aVWhat the naked eye perceives as a single star is actually a binary star system, consisting of a white main-sequence star of spectral type A1V, termed Sirius A, and a faint white dwarf companion of spectral type DA2, called Sirius B.
p136
aVThe distance separating Sirius A from its companion varies between 8.1 and 31.5 AU.
p137
aVSirius appears bright because of both its intrinsic luminosity and its proximity to Earth.
p138
aVAt a distance of 2.6 parsecs (8.6 ly), as determined by the Hipparcos astrometry satellite, the Sirius system is one of Earth's near neighbors; for Northern-hemisphere observers between 30 degrees and 73 degrees of latitude (including almost all of Europe and North America), it is the closest star (after the Sun) that can be seen with a naked eye.
p139
aVSirius is gradually moving closer to the Solar System, so it will slightly increase in brightness over the next 60,000 years.
p140
aVAfter that time its distance will begin to recede, but it will continue to be the brightest star in the Earth's sky for the next 210,000 years.
p141
aVSirius A is about twice as massive as the Sun and has an absolute visual magnitude of 1.42.
p142
aVIt is 25 times more luminous than the Sun but has a significantly lower luminosity than other bright stars such as Canopus or Rigel.
p143
aVThe system is between 200 and 300 million years old.
p144
aVIt was originally composed of two bright bluish stars.
p145
aVThe more massive of these, Sirius B, consumed its resources and became a red giant before shedding its outer layers and collapsing into its current state as a white dwarf around 120 million years ago.
p146
aVSirius is also known colloquially as the "Dog Star", reflecting its prominence in its constellation, Canis Major (Greater Dog).
p147
aVThe heliacal rising of Sirius marked the flooding of the Nile in Ancient Egypt and the "dog days" of summer for the ancient Greeks, while to the Polynesians it marked winter and was an important star for navigation around the Pacific Ocean.
